{"id":"quant-ph/0210057","submitter":"Lorenza Viola","authors":"Evan M. Fortunato, Lorenza Viola, Marco A. Pravia, Emanuel Knill,\n  Raymond Laflamme, Timothy F. Havel, David G. Cory","title":"Exploring Noiseless Subsystems via Nuclear Magnetic Resonance","comments":"21 pages, 5 encapsulated eps figures, REVTeX4. Substantially expanded\n  description of work reported in Science 293, 2059 (2000), including\n  additional theoretical considerations and experimental results","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.67.062303","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Noiseless subsystems offer a general and efficient method for protecting\nquantum information in the presence of noise that has symmetry properties. A\nparadigmatic class of error models displaying non-trivial symmetries emerges\nunder collective noise behavior, which implies a permutationally-invariant\ninteraction between the system and the environment. We describe experiments\ndemonstrating the preservation of a bit of quantum information encoded in a\nthree qubit noiseless subsystem for general collective noise. A complete set of\ninput states is used to determine the super-operator for the implemented\none-qubit process and to confirm that the fidelity of entanglement is improved\nfor a large, non-commutative set of engineered errors. To date, this is the\nlargest set of error operators that has been successfully corrected for by any\nquantum code.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Oct 2002 01:40:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0210058","submitter":"Robert C. Bishop","authors":"Robert C. Bishop","title":"Quantum Time Arrows, Semigroups and Time-Reversal in Scattering","comments":"10 pages, accepted for publication in the International Journal of\n  Theoretical Physics, presented at the International Quantum Structures\n  Association Sixth Biennial Meeting, Vienna, Austria, 1-7 July 2002; corrected\n  minor typographical errors","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Two approaches toward the arrow of time for scattering processes have been\nproposed in rigged Hilbert space quantum mechanics. One, due to Arno Bohm,\ninvolves preparations and registrations in laboratory operations and results in\ntwo semigroups oriented in the forward direction of time. The other, employed\nby the Brussels-Austin group, is more general, involving excitations and\nde-excitations of systems, and apparently results in two semigroups oriented in\nopposite directions of time. It turns out that these two time arrows can be\nrelated to each other via Wigner's extensions of the spacetime symmetry group.\nFurthermore, their are subtle differences in causality as well as the\npossibilities for the existence and creation of time-reversed states depending\non which time arrow is chosen.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Oct 2002 09:30:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 1 Oct 2003 10:42:05 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 20 Mar 2004 20:08:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
